    #[test]
    fn test_generate_split_suggestions_empty_communities() {
        let temp_dir = TempDir::new().unwrap();
        let file_path = temp_dir.path().join(&quot;test.py&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;file_path, &quot;# test&quot;).unwrap();
        
        let config = create_test_config();
        let analyzer = FileAnalyzer::new(config);
        
        let communities = Vec::new();
        let suggestions = analyzer.generate_split_suggestions(&amp;file_path, &amp;communities).unwrap();
        
        // Should generate default splits when no communities found
        assert_eq!(suggestions.len(), 2);
        assert!(suggestions.iter().all(|s| s.name.contains(&quot;test&quot;)));
    }

    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_discover_large_files() {
        let temp_dir = TempDir::new().unwrap();
        let root_path = temp_dir.path();
        
        // Create a large file
        let large_file = root_path.join(&quot;large.py&quot;);
        let content = &quot;def hello():\n    return &#x27;world&#x27;\n&quot;.repeat(30);
        fs::write(&amp;large_file, content).unwrap();
        
        // Create a small file
        let small_file = root_path.join(&quot;small.py&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;small_file, &quot;print(&#x27;hello&#x27;)&quot;).unwrap();
        
        let config = create_test_config();
        let analyzer = FileAnalyzer::new(config);
        
        let large_files = analyzer.discover_large_files(root_path).await.unwrap();
        
        // Should find the large file but not the small one
        assert!(large_files.contains(&amp;large_file));
        assert!(!large_files.contains(&amp;small_file));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_extract_imports_by_extension() {
        let temp_dir = TempDir::new().unwrap();
        let config = create_test_config();
        let analyzer = FileAnalyzer::new(config);
        
        // Test Python file
        let py_file = temp_dir.path().join(&quot;test.py&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;py_file, &quot;import os&quot;).unwrap();
        let py_imports = analyzer.extract_imports(&amp;py_file).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(py_imports.len(), 1);
        
        // Test JavaScript file
        let js_file = temp_dir.path().join(&quot;test.js&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;js_file, &quot;import React from &#x27;react&#x27;;&quot;).unwrap();
        let js_imports = analyzer.extract_imports(&amp;js_file).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(js_imports.len(), 1);
        
        // Test Rust file
        let rs_file = temp_dir.path().join(&quot;test.rs&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;rs_file, &quot;use std::collections::HashMap;&quot;).unwrap();
        let rs_imports = analyzer.extract_imports(&amp;rs_file).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(rs_imports.len(), 1);
        
        // Test unsupported file
        let txt_file = temp_dir.path().join(&quot;test.txt&quot;);
        fs::write(&amp;txt_file, &quot;some text&quot;).unwrap();
        let txt_imports = analyzer.extract_imports(&amp;txt_file).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(txt_imports.len(), 0);
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_collect_large_files_recursive_skips_directories() {
        let temp_dir = TempDir::new().unwrap();
        let root_path = temp_dir.path();
        
        // Create node_modules directory (should be skipped)
        let node_modules = root_path.join(&quot;node_modules&quot;);
        fs::create_dir(&amp;node_modules).unwrap();
        let large_file_in_node_modules = node_modules.join(&quot;large.js&quot;);
        let content = &quot;function test() { return &#x27;test&#x27;; }\n&quot;.repeat(30);
        fs::write(&amp;large_file_in_node_modules, content).unwrap();
        
        let config = create_test_config();
        let analyzer = FileAnalyzer::new(config);
        
        let mut files = Vec::new();
        analyzer.collect_large_files_recursive(root_path, &amp;mut files).unwrap();
        
        // Should not find the file in node_modules
        assert!(!files.contains(&amp;large_file_in_node_modules));
    }
}
📄 datasets/code-smells-python/command-line-shell/after/src/shell/core.py
from typing import Callable
from colorama import Fore as f

SHELL_HEADER = f&quot;  {f.YELLOW}[*] {f.CYAN}-&gt; {f.WHITE}&quot;
COMMANDS: dict[str, Callable[[list[str]], None]] = {}

def add_command(command: str, function: Callable[[list[str]], None]) -&gt; None:
    COMMANDS[command] = function

def execute(command: str, arguments: list[str]) -&gt; None:
    if command in COMMANDS:
        COMMANDS[command](arguments)

def parse_command_string(command_string: str) -&gt; tuple[str, list[str]]:
    # Split the input string into a list of strings at each space character
    command_parts = command_string.split()

    # If the command is empty, return an empty command and an empty list of arguments
    if not command_parts:
        return &quot;&quot;, []

    # Extract the command (the first element in the list) and the arguments (the rest of the list)
    command = command_parts[0].lower().strip()
    arguments = [part.strip() for part in command_parts[1:]]

    return command, arguments

def shell_input() -&gt; tuple[str, list[str]]:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Gets User input then returns a parsed command.&quot;&quot;&quot;
    user_input = input(SHELL_HEADER)
    return parse_command_string(user_input)

def run_shell() -&gt; None:
    while True:
        command, arguments = shell_input()
        execute(command, arguments)
📄 docs/development/CI_CD_INTEGRATION.md
# CI/CD Integration Guide

This guide provides comprehensive instructions for integrating Valknut into your CI/CD pipelines for automated code quality enforcement.

## Table of Contents
- [Overview](#overview)
- [Quality Gates](#quality-gates)
- [GitHub Actions](#github-actions)
- [Jenkins](#jenkins)
- [GitLab CI](#gitlab-ci)
- [Azure DevOps](#azure-devops)
- [CircleCI](#circleci)
- [SonarQube Integration](#sonarqube-integration)
- [Custom Integration](#custom-integration)
- [Best Practices](#best-practices)
- [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)

## Overview

Valknut provides robust CI/CD integration through:

- **Quality Gates**: Configurable failure conditions with exit codes
- **Multiple Output Formats**: JSON, SonarQube, CSV for different tools  
- **Performance Optimization**: Fast analysis suitable for CI environments
- **Comprehensive Reporting**: Detailed reports for team review
- **Flexible Configuration**: Adaptable to different project standards

### Key Benefits

- **Automated Quality Enforcement**: Prevent quality regressions automatically
- **Configurable Standards**: Set team-specific quality thresholds
- **Rich Reporting**: Generate reports for stakeholders
- **Integration Flexibility**: Works with any CI/CD system
- **Performance Optimized**: Fast enough for every commit/PR

## Quality Gates

Quality gates enable automated pass/fail decisions based on code quality metrics.

### Basic Quality Gate Setup

```bash
# Enable quality gates with default thresholds
valknut analyze --quality-gate ./src

# Fail on any issues found
valknut analyze --fail-on-issues ./src

# Custom thresholds
valknut analyze \
  --quality-gate \
  --max-complexity 75 \
  --min-health 60 \
  --max-debt 30 \
  --max-issues 50 \
  --max-critical 0 \
  ./src
```

### Quality Gate Configuration

| Threshold | CLI Option | Range | Default | Description |
|-----------|------------|-------|---------|-------------|
| Max Complexity | `--max-complexity` | 0-100 | 75 | Maximum complexity score (lower is better) |
| Min Health | `--min-health` | 0-100 | 60 | Minimum health score (higher is better) |
| Max Debt | `--max-debt` | 0-100% | 30 | Maximum technical debt ratio |
| Min Maintainability | `--min-maintainability` | 0-100 | 20 | Minimum maintainability index |
| Max Issues | `--max-issues` | 0+ | 50 | Maximum total issues |
| Max Critical | `--max-critical` | 0+ | 0 | Maximum critical issues |
| Max High Priority | `--max-high-priority` | 0+ | 5 | Maximum high-priority issues |

### Exit Codes

| Code | Status | Description |
|------|--------|-------------|
| 0 | ✅ Success | Analysis completed, quality gates passed |
| 1 | ❌ Quality Gate Failure | One or more thresholds exceeded |
| 2 | ⚠️ Configuration Error | Invalid arguments or configuration |
| 3 | ⚠️ File System Error | Path or permission issues |
| 4 | ⚠️ Analysis Error | Internal analysis engine error |

## GitHub Actions

### Basic Quality Gate Workflow

```yaml
name: Code Quality Gate
on:
  push:
    branches: [ main, develop ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  quality-gate:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    
    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
      
    - name: Setup Rust
      uses: actions-rs/toolchain@v1
      with:
        toolchain: stable
        
    - name: Install Valknut
      run: |
        cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
        
    - name: Run Quality Gate
      run: |
        valknut analyze \
          --quality-gate \
          --max-complexity 75 \
          --min-health 60 \
          --max-debt 30 \
          --format ci-summary \
          --out quality-reports/ \
          ./src
          
    - name: Upload Quality Reports
      uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
      if: always()
      with:
        name: quality-reports
        path: quality-reports/
        retention-days: 30
```

### Advanced GitHub Actions Setup

```yaml
name: Comprehensive Code Analysis
on:
  push:
    branches: [ main, develop ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

env:
  VALKNUT_VERSION: &quot;latest&quot;

jobs:
  quality-analysis:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    
    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
      with:
        fetch-depth: 0  # Full history for better analysis
        
    - name: Cache Valknut installation
      uses: actions/cache@v4
      with:
        path: ~/.cargo/bin/valknut
        key: valknut-${{ env.VALKNUT_VERSION }}
        
    - name: Install Valknut
      run: |
        if [ ! -f ~/.cargo/bin/valknut ]; then
          cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
        fi
        
    - name: Create Quality Gate Configuration
      run: |
        cat &gt; .valknut.yml &lt;&lt; EOF
        analysis:
          enable_structure_analysis: true
          enable_complexity_analysis: true
          enable_refactoring_analysis: true
          enable_names_analysis: true
          max_files: 1000
        
        quality_gates:
          enabled: true
          max_complexity: 75
          min_health: 60
          max_debt: 30
          max_issues: 50
          max_critical: 0
          max_high_priority: 5
        EOF
        
    - name: Run Comprehensive Analysis
      run: |
        valknut analyze \
          --config .valknut.yml \
          --quality-gate \
          --format json \
          --out reports/ \
          ./src
          
    - name: Generate Team Report
      run: |
        valknut analyze \
          --config .valknut.yml \
          --format html \
          --out reports/html/ \
          ./src
          
    - name: Comment PR with Results
      if: github.event_name == &#x27;pull_request&#x27;
      uses: actions/github-script@v7
      with:
        script: |
          const fs = require(&#x27;fs&#x27;);
          const path = &#x27;reports/ci-summary.json&#x27;;
          
          if (fs.existsSync(path)) {
            const report = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(path, &#x27;utf8&#x27;));
            const comment = `## 🔍 Code Quality Report
            
            **Health Score**: ${report.health_metrics.overall_health_score.toFixed(1)}/100
            **Complexity Score**: ${report.health_metrics.complexity_score.toFixed(1)}/100
            **Technical Debt**: ${report.health_metrics.technical_debt_ratio.toFixed(1)}%
            
            **Issues Found**: ${report.summary.total_issues}
            - Critical: ${report.summary.critical_issues}
            - High Priority: ${report.summary.high_priority_issues}
            
            [View Detailed Report](https://github.com/${{ github.repository }}/actions/runs/${{ github.run_id }})
            `;
            
            github.rest.issues.createComment({
              issue_number: context.issue.number,
              owner: context.repo.owner,
              repo: context.repo.repo,
              body: comment
            });
          }
          
    - name: Upload Reports
      uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
      if: always()
      with:
        name: code-quality-reports
        path: reports/
        retention-days: 90
```

### Matrix Strategy for Multiple Languages

```yaml
name: Multi-Language Quality Gate
on: [push, pull_request]

jobs:
  quality-gate:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    strategy:
      matrix:
        language:
          - { name: &quot;python&quot;, path: &quot;./python-service&quot;, config: &quot;python-config.yml&quot; }
          - { name: &quot;typescript&quot;, path: &quot;./web-app&quot;, config: &quot;web-config.yml&quot; }
          - { name: &quot;rust&quot;, path: &quot;./rust-service&quot;, config: &quot;rust-config.yml&quot; }
    
    steps:
    - uses: actions/checkout@v4
    
    - name: Install Valknut
      run: cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
      
    - name: Run Quality Gate for ${{ matrix.language.name }}
      run: |
        valknut analyze \
          --config configs/${{ matrix.language.config }} \
          --quality-gate \
          --format ci-summary \
          --out reports/${{ matrix.language.name }}/ \
          ${{ matrix.language.path }}
```

## Jenkins

### Basic Jenkins Pipeline

```groovy
pipeline {
    agent any
    
    environment {
        VALKNUT_VERSION = &#x27;latest&#x27;
    }
    
    stages {
        stage(&#x27;Checkout&#x27;) {
            steps {
                checkout scm
            }
        }
        
        stage(&#x27;Install Valknut&#x27;) {
            steps {
                sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    if [ ! -f ~/.cargo/bin/valknut ]; then
                        curl --proto &#x27;=https&#x27; --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- -y
                        source ~/.cargo/env
                        cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
                    fi
                &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
            }
        }
        
        stage(&#x27;Quality Gate&#x27;) {
            steps {
                sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
                      --quality-gate \
                      --max-complexity 75 \
                      --min-health 60 \
                      --max-debt 30 \
                      --format ci-summary \
                      --out quality-reports/ \
                      ./src
                &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
            }
        }
        
        stage(&#x27;Generate Reports&#x27;) {
            steps {
                sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
                      --format html \
                      --out reports/html/ \
                      ./src
                &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
            }
        }
    }
    
    post {
        always {
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: &#x27;quality-reports/**/*&#x27;, fingerprint: true
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: &#x27;reports/**/*&#x27;, fingerprint: true
        }
        
        failure {
            emailext (
                subject: &quot;Quality Gate Failed: ${env.JOB_NAME} - ${env.BUILD_NUMBER}&quot;,
                body: &quot;The code quality gate failed. Check the build logs and quality reports.&quot;,
                to: &quot;${env.CHANGE_AUTHOR_EMAIL}&quot;
            )
        }
    }
}
```

### Advanced Jenkins Pipeline with Quality Gates

```groovy
pipeline {
    agent any
    
    parameters {
        choice(
            name: &#x27;QUALITY_LEVEL&#x27;,
            choices: [&#x27;strict&#x27;, &#x27;normal&#x27;, &#x27;permissive&#x27;],
            description: &#x27;Quality gate strictness level&#x27;
        )
        booleanParam(
            name: &#x27;GENERATE_REPORTS&#x27;,
            defaultValue: true,
            description: &#x27;Generate detailed HTML reports&#x27;
        )
    }
    
    environment {
        QUALITY_CONFIG = getQualityConfig(params.QUALITY_LEVEL)
    }
    
    stages {
        stage(&#x27;Setup&#x27;) {
            steps {
                script {
                    // Install Valknut if not cached
                    sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                        if [ ! -f ~/.cargo/bin/valknut ]; then
                            curl --proto &#x27;=https&#x27; --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- -y
                            source ~/.cargo/env
                            cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
                        fi
                    &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                }
            }
        }
        
        stage(&#x27;Quality Gate&#x27;) {
            steps {
                script {
                    def qualityArgs = getQualityArgs(params.QUALITY_LEVEL)
                    sh &quot;&quot;&quot;
                        ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze ${qualityArgs} \
                          --quality-gate \
                          --format ci-summary \
                          --out quality-reports/ \
                          ./src
                    &quot;&quot;&quot;
                }
            }
        }
        
        stage(&#x27;Generate Reports&#x27;) {
            when {
                expression { params.GENERATE_REPORTS }
            }
            parallel {
                stage(&#x27;HTML Report&#x27;) {
                    steps {
                        sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
                              --format html \
                              --out reports/html/ \
                              ./src
                        &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    }
                }
                stage(&#x27;Markdown Summary&#x27;) {
                    steps {
                        sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
                              --format markdown \
                              --out reports/markdown/ \
                              ./src
                        &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    }
                }
                stage(&#x27;CSV Export&#x27;) {
                    steps {
                        sh &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
                              --format csv \
                              --out reports/csv/ \
                              ./src
                        &#x27;&#x27;&#x27;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    
    post {
        always {
            publishHTML([
                allowMissing: false,
                alwaysLinkToLastBuild: true,
                keepAll: true,
                reportDir: &#x27;reports/html&#x27;,
                reportFiles: &#x27;index.html&#x27;,
                reportName: &#x27;Code Quality Report&#x27;
            ])
            
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: &#x27;quality-reports/**/*&#x27;, fingerprint: true
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: &#x27;reports/**/*&#x27;, fingerprint: true
        }
        
        failure {
            script {
                def reportPath = &#x27;quality-reports/ci-summary.json&#x27;
                if (fileExists(reportPath)) {
                    def report = readJSON file: reportPath
                    def message = &quot;&quot;&quot;
                    Quality Gate Failed!
                    
                    Health Score: ${report.health_metrics.overall_health_score}/100
                    Issues Found: ${report.summary.total_issues}
                    Critical Issues: ${report.summary.critical_issues}
                    
                    View detailed report: ${env.BUILD_URL}Code_Quality_Report/
                    &quot;&quot;&quot;
                    
                    slackSend(
                        channel: &#x27;#code-quality&#x27;,
                        color: &#x27;danger&#x27;,
                        message: message
                    )
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

def getQualityArgs(level) {
    switch(level) {
        case &#x27;strict&#x27;:
            return &#x27;--max-complexity 60 --min-health 70 --max-debt 20 --max-issues 25 --max-critical 0&#x27;
        case &#x27;normal&#x27;:
            return &#x27;--max-complexity 75 --min-health 60 --max-debt 30 --max-issues 50 --max-critical 0&#x27;
        case &#x27;permissive&#x27;:
            return &#x27;--max-complexity 85 --min-health 40 --max-debt 50 --max-issues 100 --max-critical 5&#x27;
        default:
            return &#x27;--max-complexity 75 --min-health 60 --max-debt 30 --max-issues 50 --max-critical 0&#x27;
    }
}
```

## GitLab CI

### Basic GitLab CI Configuration

```yaml
# .gitlab-ci.yml
stages:
  - quality-gate
  - reports

variables:
  VALKNUT_VERSION: &quot;latest&quot;

before_script:
  - apt-get update -qq &amp;&amp; apt-get install -y -qq curl build-essential
  - curl --proto &#x27;=https&#x27; --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- -y
  - source ~/.cargo/env
  - cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut

quality-gate:
  stage: quality-gate
  script:
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --quality-gate \
        --max-complexity 75 \
        --min-health 60 \
        --max-debt 30 \
        --format ci-summary \
        --out quality-reports/ \
        ./src
  artifacts:
    when: always
    expire_in: 1 week
    reports:
      junit: quality-reports/junit.xml
    paths:
      - quality-reports/
  rules:
    - if: $CI_PIPELINE_SOURCE == &quot;merge_request_event&quot;
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH

generate-reports:
  stage: reports
  script:
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --format html \
        --out reports/html/ \
        ./src
  artifacts:
    expire_in: 30 days
    paths:
      - reports/
  pages:
    stage: deploy
    script:
      - mkdir public
      - cp -r reports/html/* public/
    artifacts:
      paths:
        - public
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH
```

### Advanced GitLab CI with Docker

```yaml
# .gitlab-ci.yml
image: rust:1.70

variables:
  DOCKER_DRIVER: overlay2
  CARGO_HOME: $CI_PROJECT_DIR/.cargo

cache:
  paths:
    - .cargo/
    - target/

stages:
  - build
  - quality-gate
  - security
  - reports
  - deploy

# Custom Docker image with Valknut pre-installed
.valknut_base:
  image: registry.gitlab.com/your-org/valknut-ci:latest
  before_script:
    - valknut --version

quality-gate:
  extends: .valknut_base
  stage: quality-gate
  script:
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --config .valknut-ci.yml \
        --quality-gate \
        --format ci-summary \
        --out quality-reports/ \
        ./src
    - |
      # Custom script to parse results and set GitLab variables
      python3 scripts/parse_quality_results.py quality-reports/ci-summary.json
  artifacts:
    when: always
    expire_in: 1 week
    reports:
      junit: quality-reports/junit.xml
    paths:
      - quality-reports/
  variables:
    QUALITY_GATE_ENABLED: &quot;true&quot;

security-scan:
  extends: .valknut_base
  stage: security
  script:
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --config .valknut-security.yml \
        --fail-on-issues \
        --max-critical 0 \
        --format sonar \
        --out security-reports/ \
        ./src
  artifacts:
    reports:
      sast: security-reports/security-report.json
  allow_failure: false

comprehensive-report:
  extends: .valknut_base
  stage: reports
  script:
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --format html \
        --out reports/html/ \
        ./src
    - |
      valknut analyze \
        --format markdown \
        --out reports/markdown/ \
        ./src
  artifacts:
    expire_in: 30 days
    paths:
      - reports/
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH
    - if: $CI_PIPELINE_SOURCE == &quot;schedule&quot;

pages:
  stage: deploy
  dependencies:
    - comprehensive-report
  script:
    - mkdir public
    - cp -r reports/html/* public/
    - echo &quot;Quality reports deployed to GitLab Pages&quot;
  artifacts:
    paths:
      - public
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH
```

```yaml
# azure-pipelines.yml

  branches:

      - README.md

  displayName: &#x27;Code Quality Gate&#x27;
  jobs:
  - job: Analysis
    displayName: &#x27;Run Code Analysis&#x27;

        key: &#x27;valknut | &quot;$(Agent.OS)&quot; | &quot;$(VALKNUT_VERSION)&quot;&#x27;

          --min-health 60 \

        testResultsFormat: &#x27;JUnit&#x27;
        testResultsFiles: &#x27;$(Agent.TempDirectory)/quality-reports/junit.xml&#x27;

      condition: always()

        targetPath: &#x27;$(Agent.TempDirectory)/quality-reports/&#x27;
        artifactName: &#x27;quality-reports&#x27;
      displayName: &#x27;Publish Quality Reports&#x27;

- stage: Security
  displayName: &#x27;Security Analysis&#x27;
  dependsOn: QualityGate
  condition: succeeded()

  - job: SecurityScan
    displayName: &#x27;Security Scan&#x27;

          --config .valknut-security.yml \

      displayName: &#x27;Run Security Analysis&#x27;

    - task: PublishPipelineArtifact@1

        artifactName: &#x27;security-reports&#x27;

# .circleci/config.yml

    steps:
      - restore_cache:
          keys:
            - valknut-v1-{{ checksum &quot;Cargo.lock&quot; }}
      - run:
          name: Install Valknut

            if [ ! -f ~/.cargo/bin/valknut ]; then
              cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut
            fi
      - save_cache:
          key: valknut-v1-{{ checksum &quot;Cargo.lock&quot; }}
          paths:
            - ~/.cargo/bin/valknut

jobs:
  quality-gate:
    executor: rust-executor
    steps:
      - checkout
      - install-valknut
      - run:
          name: Run Quality Gate
          command: |
            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
              --quality-gate \
              --max-complexity 75 \
              --min-health 60 \
              --max-debt 30 \
              --format ci-summary \
              --out quality-reports/ \
              ./src
      - store_test_results:
          path: quality-reports/
      - store_artifacts:
          path: quality-reports/
          destination: quality-reports

  comprehensive-analysis:
    executor: rust-executor
    steps:
      - checkout
      - install-valknut
      - run:
          name: Generate Comprehensive Report
          command: |
            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
              --format html \
              --out reports/html/ \
              ./src
      - run:
          name: Generate Team Report
          command: |
            ~/.cargo/bin/valknut analyze \
              --format markdown \
              --out reports/markdown/ \
              ./src
      - store_artifacts:
          path: reports/
          destination: reports

workflows:
  version: 2
  quality-check:
    jobs:
      - quality-gate
      - comprehensive-analysis:
          requires:
            - quality-gate
          filters:
            branches:
              only: main
```

## Custom Integration

### REST API Integration

For custom CI/CD systems, integrate via REST API calls:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# Custom CI script

# Run analysis and capture results
RESULT=$(valknut analyze \
  --quality-gate \
  --format json \
  --quiet \
  ./src 2&gt;&amp;1)

EXIT_CODE=$?

# Parse results and send to custom API
if [ $EXIT_CODE -eq 0 ]; then
  curl -X POST &quot;https://api.example.com/quality-reports&quot; \
    -H &quot;Content-Type: application/json&quot; \
    -H &quot;Authorization: Bearer $API_TOKEN&quot; \
    -d &quot;$RESULT&quot;
else
  curl -X POST &quot;https://api.example.com/quality-failures&quot; \
    -H &quot;Content-Type: application/json&quot; \
    -H &quot;Authorization: Bearer $API_TOKEN&quot; \
    -d &quot;{\&quot;error\&quot;: \&quot;Quality gate failed\&quot;, \&quot;details\&quot;: \&quot;$RESULT\&quot;}&quot;
fi

exit $EXIT_CODE
```

### Webhook Integration

```python
#!/usr/bin/env python3
&quot;&quot;&quot;
Custom webhook integration for Valknut results
&quot;&quot;&quot;
import json
import subprocess
import requests
import sys
from typing import Dict, Any

def run_valknut_analysis(path: str, config: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; tuple[int, str]:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Run Valknut analysis and return exit code and output&quot;&quot;&quot;
    cmd = [
        &quot;valknut&quot;, &quot;analyze&quot;,
        &quot;--quality-gate&quot;,
        &quot;--format&quot;, &quot;json&quot;,
        &quot;--out&quot;, &quot;reports/&quot;,
        path
    ]
    
    # Add quality gate options from config
    if config.get(&quot;max_complexity&quot;):
        cmd.extend([&quot;--max-complexity&quot;, str(config[&quot;max_complexity&quot;])])
    if config.get(&quot;min_health&quot;):
        cmd.extend([&quot;--min-health&quot;, str(config[&quot;min_health&quot;])])
    
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(cmd, capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=300)
        return result.returncode, result.stdout
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:
        return 4, &quot;Analysis timeout after 5 minutes&quot;

def send_webhook(webhook_url: str, data: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; None:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Send results to webhook endpoint&quot;&quot;&quot;
    try:
        response = requests.post(
            webhook_url,
            json=data,
            headers={&quot;Content-Type&quot;: &quot;application/json&quot;},
            timeout=10
        )
        response.raise_for_status()
        print(f&quot;Webhook sent successfully: {response.status_code}&quot;)
    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:
        print(f&quot;Webhook failed: {e}&quot;)

def main():
    config = {
        &quot;max_complexity&quot;: 75,
        &quot;min_health&quot;: 60,
        &quot;webhook_url&quot;: &quot;https://your-webhook-url.com/quality-reports&quot;
    }
    
    exit_code, output = run_valknut_analysis(&quot;./src&quot;, config)
    
    webhook_data = {
        &quot;status&quot;: &quot;passed&quot; if exit_code == 0 else &quot;failed&quot;,
        &quot;exit_code&quot;: exit_code,
        &quot;analysis_output&quot;: output,
        &quot;project&quot;: &quot;my-project&quot;,
        &quot;branch&quot;: os.environ.get(&quot;CI_BRANCH&quot;, &quot;unknown&quot;),
        &quot;commit&quot;: os.environ.get(&quot;CI_COMMIT&quot;, &quot;unknown&quot;)
    }
    
    send_webhook(config[&quot;webhook_url&quot;], webhook_data)
    sys.exit(exit_code)

if __name__ == &quot;__main__&quot;:
    main()
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Quality Gate Strategy

#### Gradual Implementation
```bash
# Phase 1: Monitoring only (no failures)
valknut analyze --format ci-summary ./src

# Phase 2: Permissive gates
valknut analyze --quality-gate --max-complexity 90 --min-health 30 ./src

# Phase 3: Standard gates  
valknut analyze --quality-gate --max-complexity 75 --min-health 60 ./src

# Phase 4: Strict gates
valknut analyze --quality-gate --max-complexity 60 --min-health 70 ./src
```

#### Branch-Specific Configuration
```yaml
# Different standards for different branches
- name: Quality Gate - Main Branch
  if: github.ref == &#x27;refs/heads/main&#x27;
  run: |
    valknut analyze --quality-gate \
      --max-complexity 60 --min-health 70 --max-critical 0 ./src

- name: Quality Gate - Feature Branch  
  if: github.ref != &#x27;refs/heads/main&#x27;
  run: |
    valknut analyze --quality-gate \
      --max-complexity 75 --min-health 60 --max-critical 2 ./src
```

### 2. Performance Optimization

#### Caching Strategy
```yaml
# Cache Valknut installation and analysis results
- name: Cache Valknut
  uses: actions/cache@v4
  with:
    path: |
      ~/.cargo/bin/valknut
      ~/.valknut/cache/
    key: valknut-${{ hashFiles(&#x27;**/Cargo.lock&#x27;) }}
```

#### Parallel Analysis
```bash
# Analyze different components in parallel
valknut analyze --config backend-config.yml ./backend &amp;
valknut analyze --config frontend-config.yml ./frontend &amp;
valknut analyze --config shared-config.yml ./shared &amp;
wait
```

#### Incremental Analysis
```bash
# Only analyze changed files (future feature)
git diff --name-only HEAD~1 HEAD | \
  grep -E &#x27;\.(py|js|ts|rs)$&#x27; | \
  xargs valknut analyze --quality-gate
```

### 3. Configuration Management

#### Environment-Specific Configs
```
configs/
├── development.yml     # Permissive for dev
├── staging.yml        # Standard for staging  
├── production.yml     # Strict for production
└── security.yml       # Security-focused analysis
```

#### Team-Specific Standards
```yaml
# Team A: Frontend team
analysis:
  enable_names_analysis: true
  focus_areas: [&quot;ui&quot;, &quot;components&quot;]
quality_gates:
  max_complexity: 70
  min_health: 65

# Team B: Backend team  
analysis:
  enable_security_analysis: true
  focus_areas: [&quot;api&quot;, &quot;services&quot;]
quality_gates:
  max_complexity: 75
  min_health: 60
  max_critical: 0
```

### 4. Reporting Strategy

#### Multi-Format Reports
```bash
# Generate reports for different audiences
valknut analyze --format html --out reports/executive/ ./src     # Leadership
valknut analyze --format markdown --out reports/technical/ ./src # Developers  
valknut analyze --format csv --out reports/metrics/ ./src        # Analytics
```

#### Historical Tracking
```python
# Track quality metrics over time
import json
from datetime import datetime

def store_metrics(analysis_result: dict) -&gt; None:
    timestamp = datetime.now().isoformat()
    
    metrics = {
        &quot;timestamp&quot;: timestamp,
        &quot;health_score&quot;: analysis_result[&quot;health_metrics&quot;][&quot;overall_health_score&quot;],
        &quot;complexity_score&quot;: analysis_result[&quot;health_metrics&quot;][&quot;complexity_score&quot;],
        &quot;technical_debt&quot;: analysis_result[&quot;health_metrics&quot;][&quot;technical_debt_ratio&quot;],
        &quot;total_issues&quot;: analysis_result[&quot;summary&quot;][&quot;total_issues&quot;]
    }
    
    # Store in time series database or append to file
    with open(&quot;quality-metrics.jsonl&quot;, &quot;a&quot;) as f:
        f.write(json.dumps(metrics) + &quot;\n&quot;)
```

## Troubleshooting

### Common Issues

#### 1. Installation Problems
```bash
# Problem: Cargo not found
# Solution: Install Rust toolchain
curl --proto &#x27;=https&#x27; --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
source ~/.cargo/env

# Problem: Permission denied
# Solution: Use user installation
cargo install --git https://github.com/nathanricedev/valknut --locked
```

#### 2. Quality Gate Failures
```bash
# Problem: Unexpectedly failing quality gates
# Solution: Generate detailed report for investigation
valknut analyze --verbose --format html --out debug-reports/ ./src

# Problem: False positive issues
# Solution: Adjust configuration
valknut analyze --config relaxed-config.yml --quality-gate ./src
```

#### 3. Performance Issues
```bash
# Problem: Analysis too slow for CI
# Solution: Limit scope and enable parallel processing
valknut analyze --max-files 500 --exclude-patterns &quot;**/node_modules/**&quot; ./src

# Problem: Memory usage too high
# Solution: Use streaming analysis
export VALKNUT_MEMORY_LIMIT=512MB
valknut analyze ./src
```

#### 4. Configuration Issues
```bash
# Problem: Configuration not found
# Solution: Specify absolute path
valknut analyze --config $(pwd)/.valknut.yml ./src

# Problem: Invalid configuration
# Solution: Validate before use
valknut validate-config --config .valknut.yml --verbose
```

### Debug Commands

```bash
# Enable verbose logging
valknut --verbose analyze ./src

# Rust-level debugging
RUST_LOG=debug valknut analyze ./src

# Performance profiling
RUST_LOG=valknut::performance=trace valknut analyze ./src

# Memory usage tracking
valgrind --tool=massif valknut analyze ./src
```

This guide provides comprehensive integration patterns for most CI/CD systems. Adapt the examples to your specific environment and quality standards.
📄 datasets/code-smells-python/command-line-shell/after/src/shell/api.py
from .algorithms import DECODING_ALGORITHMS, ENCODING_ALGORITHMS, HASHING_ALGORITHMS

def encoding_algos() -&gt; list[str]:
    return list(ENCODING_ALGORITHMS.keys())

def decoding_algos() -&gt; list[str]:
    return list(DECODING_ALGORITHMS.keys())

def hashing_algos() -&gt; list[str]:
    return list(HASHING_ALGORITHMS.keys())

def has_encoding_algo(algo: str) -&gt; bool:
    return algo.lower().strip() in ENCODING_ALGORITHMS

def has_decoding_algo(algo: str) -&gt; bool:
    return algo.lower().strip() in DECODING_ALGORITHMS

def has_hashing_algo(algo: str) -&gt; bool:
    return algo.lower().strip() in HASHING_ALGORITHMS

def encode(text: str | bytes, algo: str) -&gt; str:
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = text.encode()
    encoding_fn = ENCODING_ALGORITHMS[algo.lower().strip()]
    return encoding_fn(text).decode()

def decode(text: str | bytes, algo: str) -&gt; str:
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = text.encode()
    decoding_fn = DECODING_ALGORITHMS[algo.lower().strip()]
    return decoding_fn(text).decode()

def hash_val(text: str | bytes, algo: str) -&gt; str:
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = text.encode()
    hashing_fn = HASHING_ALGORITHMS[algo.lower().strip()]
    return hashing_fn(text).hexdigest()
📄 datasets/code-smells-python/vehicle-registry-system/after.py
&quot;&quot;&quot;
Basic example of a Vehicle registration system.
&quot;&quot;&quot;
import random
import string
from dataclasses import dataclass
from datetime import datetime
from enum import Enum, auto
from typing import Optional, Tuple


class FuelType(Enum):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Types of fuel used in a vehicle.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    ELECTRIC = auto()
    PETROL = auto()


class RegistryStatus(Enum):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Possible statuses for the vehicle registry system.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    ONLINE = auto()
    CONNECTION_ERROR = auto()
    OFFLINE = auto()


taxes = {FuelType.ELECTRIC: 0.02, FuelType.PETROL: 0.05}


@dataclass
class VehicleInfoMissingError(Exception):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Custom error that is raised when vehicle information is missing for a particular brand.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    brand: str
    model: str
    message: str = &quot;Vehicle information is missing.&quot;


@dataclass
class VehicleModelInfo:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class that contains basic information about a vehicle model.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    brand: str
    model: str
    catalogue_price: int
    fuel_type: FuelType = FuelType.ELECTRIC
    production_year: int = datetime.now().year

    @property
    def tax(self) -&gt; float:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Tax to be paid when registering a vehicle of this type.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        tax_percentage = taxes[self.fuel_type]
        return tax_percentage * self.catalogue_price

    def __str__(self) -&gt; str:
        return f&quot;brand: {self.brand} - type: {self.model} - tax: {self.tax}&quot;


@dataclass
class Vehicle:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class representing a vehicle (electric or fossil fuel).&quot;&quot;&quot;

    vehicle_id: str
    license_plate: str
    info: VehicleModelInfo

    def __str__(self) -&gt; str:
        return f&quot;Id: {self.vehicle_id}. License plate: {self.license_plate}. Info: {self.info}.&quot;


class VehicleRegistry:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class representing a basic vehicle registration system.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def __init__(self) -&gt; None:
        self.vehicle_models: dict[Tuple[str, str], VehicleModelInfo] = {}
        self.online = True

    def add_model_info(self, model_info: VehicleModelInfo) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for adding a VehicleModelInfo object to a list.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        self.vehicle_models[(model_info.brand, model_info.model)] = model_info

    def find_model_info(self, brand: str, model: str) -&gt; Optional[VehicleModelInfo]:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Finds vehicle model info for a brand and model. If no info can be found, None is returned.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return self.vehicle_models.get((brand, model))

    # Below is the function used before changing self.vehicle_models to a dictionary
    # def find_model_info(self, brand: str, model: str) -&gt; Optional[VehicleModelInfo]:
    #     &quot;&quot;&quot;Finds vehicle info for a brand and model. If no info can be found, None is returned.&quot;&quot;&quot;
    #     for vehicle_model in self.vehicle_models:
    #         if vehicle_model.brand != brand or vehicle_model.model != model:
    #             continue
    #         return vehicle_model
    #     return None

    @staticmethod
    def generate_vehicle_id(length: int) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for generating a random vehicle id.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return &quot;&quot;.join(random.choices(string.ascii_uppercase, k=length))

    @staticmethod
    def generate_vehicle_license(vehicle_id: str) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for generating a vehicle license number.&quot;&quot;&quot;

        digit_part = &quot;&quot;.join(random.choices(string.digits, k=2))
        letter_part = &quot;&quot;.join(random.choices(string.ascii_uppercase, k=2))
        return f&quot;{vehicle_id[:2]}-{digit_part}-{letter_part}&quot;

    def register_vehicle(self, brand: str, model: str) -&gt; Vehicle:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Register a new vehicle and generates an id and a license plate.&quot;&quot;&quot;

        # without the walrus operator
        # vehicle_model = self.find_model_info(brand, model)
        # if not vehicle_model:
        #     raise VehicleInfoMissingError(brand, model)

        # with the walrus operator
        if not (vehicle_model := self.find_model_info(brand, model)):
            raise VehicleInfoMissingError(brand, model)

        # generate the vehicle id and license plate
        vehicle_id = self.generate_vehicle_id(12)
        license_plate = self.generate_vehicle_license(vehicle_id)
        return Vehicle(vehicle_id, license_plate, vehicle_model)

    def online_status(self) -&gt; RegistryStatus:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Report whether the registry system is online.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        if not self.online:
            return RegistryStatus.OFFLINE
        return (
            RegistryStatus.CONNECTION_ERROR
            if len(self.vehicle_models) == 0
            else RegistryStatus.ONLINE
        )


def main() -&gt; None:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Main function.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    # create a registry instance
    registry = VehicleRegistry()

    # add a couple of different vehicle models
    registry.add_model_info(VehicleModelInfo(&quot;Tesla&quot;, &quot;Model 3&quot;, 50000))
    registry.add_model_info(VehicleModelInfo(&quot;Volkswagen&quot;, &quot;ID3&quot;, 35000))
    registry.add_model_info(VehicleModelInfo(&quot;BMW&quot;, &quot;520e&quot;, 60000, FuelType.PETROL))
    registry.add_model_info(VehicleModelInfo(&quot;Tesla&quot;, &quot;Model Y&quot;, 55000))

    # verify that the registry is online
    print(f&quot;Registry status: {registry.online_status()}&quot;)

    vehicle = registry.register_vehicle(&quot;Volkswagen&quot;, &quot;ID3&quot;)

    # print out the vehicle information
    print(vehicle)


if __name__ == &quot;__main__&quot;:
    main()

Basic example of a Vehicle registration system.

from dataclasses import dataclass
from enum import Enum, auto
from random import *
from string import *


class FuelType(Enum):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Types of fuel used in a vehicle.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    ELECTRIC = auto()
    PETROL = auto()


class RegistryStatus(Enum):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Possible statuses for the vehicle registry system.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    ONLINE = auto()
    CONNECTION_ERROR = auto()
    OFFLINE = auto()


taxes = {FuelType.ELECTRIC: 0.02, FuelType.PETROL: 0.05}


@dataclass
class VehicleInfoMissingError(Exception):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Custom error that is raised when vehicle information is missing for a particular brand.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    brand: str
    model: str
    message: str = &quot;Vehicle information is missing.&quot;


@dataclass
class VehicleModelInfo:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class that contains basic information about a vehicle model.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    brand: str
    model: str
    catalogue_price: int
    fuel_type: FuelType
    production_year: int

    @property
    def tax(self) -&gt; float:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Tax to be paid when registering a vehicle of this type.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        tax_percentage = taxes[self.fuel_type]
        return tax_percentage * self.catalogue_price

    def get_info_str(self) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;String representation of this instance.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return f&quot;brand: {self.brand} - type: {self.model} - tax: {self.tax}&quot;


@dataclass
class Vehicle:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class representing a vehicle (electric or fossil fuel).&quot;&quot;&quot;

    vehicle_id: str
    license_plate: str
    info: VehicleModelInfo

    def to_string(self) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;String representation of this instance.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        info_str = self.info.get_info_str()
        return f&quot;Id: {self.vehicle_id}. License plate: {self.license_plate}. Info: {info_str}.&quot;


class VehicleRegistry:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Class representing a basic vehicle registration system.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def __init__(self) -&gt; None:
        self.vehicle_models: list[VehicleModelInfo] = []
        self.online = True

    def add_vehicle_model_info(
        self,
        brand: str,
        model: str,
        catalogue_price: int,
        fuel_type: FuelType,
        year: int,
    ) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for adding a VehicleModelInfo object to a list.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        self.vehicle_models.append(
            VehicleModelInfo(brand, model, catalogue_price, fuel_type, year)
        )

    def generate_vehicle_id(self, length: int) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for generating a random vehicle id.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return &quot;&quot;.join(choices(ascii_uppercase, k=length))

    def generate_vehicle_license(self, _id: str) -&gt; str:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Helper method for generating a vehicle license number.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return f&quot;{_id[:2]}-{&#x27;&#x27;.join(choices(digits, k=2))}-{&#x27;&#x27;.join(choices(ascii_uppercase, k=2))}&quot;

    def register_vehicle(self, brand: str, model: str) -&gt; Vehicle:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Create a new vehicle and generate an id and a license plate.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        for vehicle_info in self.vehicle_models:
            if vehicle_info.brand == brand:
                if vehicle_info.model == model:
                    vehicle_id = self.generate_vehicle_id(12)
                    license_plate = self.generate_vehicle_license(vehicle_id)
                    return Vehicle(vehicle_id, license_plate, vehicle_info)
        raise VehicleInfoMissingError(brand, model)

    def online_status(self) -&gt; RegistryStatus:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Report whether the registry system is online.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return (
            RegistryStatus.OFFLINE
            if not self.online
            else RegistryStatus.CONNECTION_ERROR
            if len(self.vehicle_models) == 0
            else RegistryStatus.ONLINE
        )


if __name__ == &quot;__main__&quot;:

    # create a registry instance
    registry = VehicleRegistry()

    # add a couple of different vehicle models
    registry.add_vehicle_model_info(&quot;Tesla&quot;, &quot;Model 3&quot;, 50000, FuelType.ELECTRIC, 2021)
    registry.add_vehicle_model_info(&quot;Volkswagen&quot;, &quot;ID3&quot;, 35000, FuelType.ELECTRIC, 2021)
    registry.add_vehicle_model_info(&quot;BMW&quot;, &quot;520e&quot;, 60000, FuelType.PETROL, 2021)
    registry.add_vehicle_model_info(&quot;Tesla&quot;, &quot;Model Y&quot;, 55000, FuelType.ELECTRIC, 2021)

    # verify that the registry is online
    print(f&quot;Registry status: {registry.online_status()}&quot;)

    # register a new vehicle
    vehicle = registry.register_vehicle(&quot;Volkswagen&quot;, &quot;ID3&quot;)

    # print out the vehicle information
    print(vehicle.to_string())

from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from dataclasses import dataclass
from enum import Enum, auto
from typing import List

FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT = 5  # The fixed nr of vacation days that can be paid out.


class VacationDaysShortageError(Exception):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Custom error that is raised when not enough vacation days are available.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def __init__(self, requested_days: int, remaining_days: int, message: str) -&gt; None:
        self.requested_days = requested_days
        self.remaining_days = remaining_days
        self.message = message
        super().__init__(message)


class Role(Enum):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Employee roles&quot;&quot;&quot;

    PRESIDENT = auto()
    VICEPRESIDENT = auto()
    MANAGER = auto()
    LEAD = auto()
    WORKER = auto()
    INTERN = auto()


@dataclass
class Employee(ABC):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Basic representation of an employee at the company.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    name: str
    role: Role
    vacation_days: int = 25

    @abstractmethod
    def pay(self) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Method to call when paying an employee&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def take_a_holiday(self) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Let the employee take a holiday (lazy bastard)&quot;&quot;&quot;
        if self.vacation_days &lt; 1:
            raise VacationDaysShortageError(
                requested_days=1,
                remaining_days=self.vacation_days,
                message=&quot;You don&#x27;t have any holidays left. Now back to work, you!&quot;,
            )
        self.vacation_days -= 1
        print(&quot;Have fun on your holiday. Don&#x27;t forget to check your emails!&quot;)

    def payout_a_holiday(self) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Let the employee get paid for unused holidays.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        # check that there are enough vacation days left for a payout
        if self.vacation_days &lt; FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT:
            raise VacationDaysShortageError(
                requested_days=FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT,
                remaining_days=self.vacation_days,
                message=&quot;You don&#x27;t have enough holidays left over for a payout&quot;,
            )
        self.vacation_days -= FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT
        print(f&quot;Paying out a holiday. Holidays left: {self.vacation_days}&quot;)


@dataclass
class HourlyEmployee(Employee):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Employee that&#x27;s paid based on number of worked hours.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    hourly_rate: float = 50
    hours_worked: int = 10

    def pay(self) -&gt; None:
        print(
            f&quot;Paying employee {self.name} a hourly rate of \
            ${self.hourly_rate} for {self.hours_worked} hours.&quot;
        )


@dataclass
class SalariedEmployee(Employee):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Employee that&#x27;s paid based on a fixed monthly salary.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    monthly_salary: float = 5000

    def pay(self) -&gt; None:
        print(
            f&quot;Paying employee {self.name} a monthly salary of ${self.monthly_salary}.&quot;
        )


class Company:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Represents a company with employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def __init__(self) -&gt; None:
        self.employees: List[Employee] = []

    def add_employee(self, employee: Employee) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Add an employee to the list of employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        self.employees.append(employee)

    def find_employees(self, role: Role) -&gt; List[Employee]:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Find all employees with a particular role in the employee list&quot;&quot;&quot;
        return [employee for employee in self.employees if employee.role is role]


def main() -&gt; None:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Main function.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    company = Company()

    company.add_employee(SalariedEmployee(name=&quot;Louis&quot;, role=Role.MANAGER))
    company.add_employee(HourlyEmployee(name=&quot;Brenda&quot;, role=Role.PRESIDENT))
    company.add_employee(HourlyEmployee(name=&quot;Tim&quot;, role=Role.INTERN))

    print(company.find_employees(role=Role.VICEPRESIDENT))
    print(company.find_employees(role=Role.MANAGER))
    print(company.find_employees(role=Role.INTERN))
    company.employees[0].pay()
    company.employees[0].take_a_holiday()


if __name__ == &quot;__main__&quot;:
    main()

import React, { useState, useEffect, useCallback } from &#x27;react&#x27;;
import { Tree } from &#x27;react-arborist&#x27;;

const TreeNode = ({ node, style, innerRef, tree }) =&gt; {
    const data = node.data;
    const isFolder = data.type === &#x27;folder&#x27;;
    const isFile = data.type === &#x27;file&#x27;;
    const isEntity = data.type === &#x27;entity&#x27;;
    
    // Priority color mapping
    const getPriorityClass = (priority) =&gt; {
        switch(priority) {
            case &#x27;critical&#x27;: return &#x27;tree-badge-Critical&#x27;;
            case &#x27;high&#x27;: return &#x27;tree-badge-High&#x27;;
            case &#x27;medium&#x27;: return &#x27;tree-badge-Medium&#x27;;
            case &#x27;low&#x27;: return &#x27;tree-badge-Low&#x27;;
            default: return &#x27;tree-badge-Low&#x27;;
        }
    };
    
    // Health score color
    const getHealthColor = (score) =&gt; {
        if (score &gt;= 0.8) return &#x27;var(--success)&#x27;;
        if (score &gt;= 0.6) return &#x27;var(--warning)&#x27;;
        return &#x27;var(--danger)&#x27;;
    };
    
    const children = [
        // Icon
        React.createElement(&#x27;i&#x27;, {
            &#x27;data-lucide&#x27;: isFolder ? &#x27;folder&#x27; : (isFile ? &#x27;file-code&#x27; : &#x27;function-square&#x27;),
            key: &#x27;icon&#x27;,
            style: { width: &#x27;16px&#x27;, height: &#x27;16px&#x27;, marginRight: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }),
        
        // Label
        React.createElement(&#x27;span&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;label&#x27;,
            style: { flex: 1, fontWeight: isFolder ? &#x27;500&#x27; : &#x27;normal&#x27; }
        }, data.name)
    ];
    
    // Health score for folders
    if (isFolder &amp;&amp; data.healthScore) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;health&#x27;,
            className: &#x27;tree-badge tree-badge-low&#x27;,
            style: { 
                backgroundColor: getHealthColor(data.healthScore) + &#x27;20&#x27;,
                color: getHealthColor(data.healthScore),
                marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27;
            }
        }, &#x27;Health: &#x27; + (data.healthScore * 100).toFixed(0) + &#x27;%&#x27;));
    }
    
    // Priority badge
    if (data.priority || data.highestPriority) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;priority&#x27;,
            className: `tree-badge ${getPriorityClass(data.priority || data.highestPriority)}`,
            style: { marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }, data.priority || data.highestPriority));
    }
    
    // Entity/file count
    if (data.entityCount || data.fileCount) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;count&#x27;,
            className: &#x27;tree-badge tree-badge-low&#x27;,
            style: { marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }, `${data.entityCount || data.fileCount} ${data.entityCount ? &#x27;entities&#x27; : &#x27;files&#x27;}`));
    }
    
    // Average score for files
    if (data.avgScore) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;score&#x27;,
            className: &#x27;tree-badge tree-badge-low complexity-score&#x27;,
            style: { marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }, `Avg: ${data.avgScore.toFixed(1)}`));
    }
    
    // Issue count for entities
    if (data.issueCount &gt; 0) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;issues&#x27;,
            className: &#x27;tree-badge tree-badge-danger&#x27;,
            style: { marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }, `${data.issueCount} issues`));
    }
    
    // Suggestion count for entities  
    if (data.suggestionCount &gt; 0) {
        children.push(React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            key: &#x27;suggestions&#x27;,
            className: &#x27;tree-badge tree-badge-info&#x27;,
            style: { marginLeft: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27; }
        }, `${data.suggestionCount} suggestions`));
    }
    
    return React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
        ref: innerRef,
        style: {
            display: &#x27;flex&#x27;,
            alignItems: &#x27;center&#x27;,
            padding: &#x27;0.5rem&#x27;,
            cursor: &#x27;pointer&#x27;,
            borderRadius: &#x27;4px&#x27;,
            border: &#x27;1px solid transparent&#x27;,
        },
        onClick: () =&gt; tree.toggle(node.id)
    }, ...children.filter(Boolean));
};

// Main tree component
const CodeAnalysisTree = ({ data }) =&gt; {
    const [treeData, setTreeData] = useState([]);
    
    // Build tree structure from file paths and directory health
    const buildTreeData = useCallback((refactoringFiles, directoryHealth) =&gt; {
        console.log(&#x27;🏗️ buildTreeData called with:&#x27;, {
            refactoringFilesCount: refactoringFiles?.length || 0,
            directoryHealthPresent: !!directoryHealth,
            directoryHealthDirs: directoryHealth?.directories ? Object.keys(directoryHealth.directories).length : 0
        });
        
        const folderMap = new Map();
        const result = [];
        
        // Add directory health data first
        if (directoryHealth &amp;&amp; directoryHealth.directories) {
            Object.entries(directoryHealth.directories).forEach(([path, health]) =&gt; {
                const pathParts = path.split(&#x27;/&#x27;).filter(Boolean);
                let currentPath = &#x27;&#x27;;
                let parentFolder = result;
                
                pathParts.forEach((part, index) =&gt; {
                    currentPath += &#x27;/&#x27; + part;
                    let folder = folderMap.get(currentPath);
                    
                    if (!folder) {
                        folder = {
                            id: &#x27;folder-&#x27; + currentPath,
                            name: String(part),
                            type: &#x27;folder&#x27;,
                            children: [],
                            healthScore: typeof health?.health_score === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.health_score : 0,
                            fileCount: typeof health?.file_count === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.file_count : 0,
                            entityCount: typeof health?.entity_count === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.entity_count : 0,
                            refactoringNeeded: Boolean(health?.refactoring_needed),
                            criticalIssues: typeof health?.critical_issues === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.critical_issues : 0,
                            highPriorityIssues: typeof health?.high_priority_issues === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.high_priority_issues : 0,
                            avgRefactoringScore: typeof health?.avg_refactoring_score === &#x27;number&#x27; ? health.avg_refactoring_score : 0
                        };
                        
                        folderMap.set(currentPath, folder);
                        parentFolder.push(folder);
                    }
                    
                    parentFolder = folder.children;
                });
            });
        }
        
        // Add refactoring files
        refactoringFiles.forEach((fileGroup, fileIndex) =&gt; {
            const pathParts = fileGroup.filePath.split(&#x27;/&#x27;).filter(Boolean);
            const fileName = pathParts.pop();
            let currentPath = &#x27;&#x27;;
            let parentFolder = result;
            
            // Navigate/create folder structure
            pathParts.forEach(part =&gt; {
                currentPath += &#x27;/&#x27; + part;
                let folder = folderMap.get(currentPath);
                
                if (!folder) {
                    folder = {
                        id: &#x27;folder-&#x27; + currentPath,
                        name: String(part),
                        type: &#x27;folder&#x27;,
                        children: []
                    };
                    folderMap.set(currentPath, folder);
                    parentFolder.push(folder);
                }
                
                parentFolder = folder.children;
            });
            
            // Add file node
            const fileNode = {
                id: &#x27;file-&#x27; + fileIndex,
                name: String(fileName),
                type: &#x27;file&#x27;,
                filePath: String(fileGroup.filePath),
                highestPriority: String(fileGroup.highestPriority || &#x27;Low&#x27;),
                entityCount: typeof fileGroup.entityCount === &#x27;number&#x27; ? fileGroup.entityCount : 0,
                avgScore: typeof fileGroup.avgScore === &#x27;number&#x27; ? fileGroup.avgScore : 0,
                totalIssues: typeof fileGroup.totalIssues === &#x27;number&#x27; ? fileGroup.totalIssues : 0,
                children: fileGroup.entities.map((entity, entityIndex) =&gt; ({
                    id: `entity-${fileIndex}-${entityIndex}`,
                    name: String(entity.name || &#x27;Unknown Entity&#x27;),
                    type: &#x27;entity&#x27;,
                    priority: String(entity.priority || &#x27;Low&#x27;),
                    score: typeof entity.score === &#x27;number&#x27; ? entity.score : 0,
                    lineRange: entity.lineRange,
                    issueCount: Array.isArray(entity.issues) ? entity.issues.length : 0,
                    suggestionCount: Array.isArray(entity.suggestions) ? entity.suggestions.length : 0,
                    children: []
                }))
            };
            
            parentFolder.push(fileNode);
        });
        
        // Sort function: directories first, then by health score/priority
        const sortNodes = (nodes) =&gt; {
            return nodes.sort((a, b) =&gt; {
                // Folders first
                if (a.type === &#x27;folder&#x27; &amp;&amp; b.type !== &#x27;folder&#x27;) return -1;
                if (b.type === &#x27;folder&#x27; &amp;&amp; a.type !== &#x27;folder&#x27;) return 1;
                
                // Sort by health score for folders (lower = more critical)
                if (a.type === &#x27;folder&#x27; &amp;&amp; b.type === &#x27;folder&#x27;) {
                    const aHealth = a.healthScore || 1;
                    const bHealth = b.healthScore || 1;
                    if (aHealth !== bHealth) return aHealth - bHealth;
                }
                
                // Sort by priority for files/entities
                const priorityOrder = { critical: 0, high: 1, medium: 2, low: 3 };
                const aPri = priorityOrder[a.priority || a.highestPriority] || 999;
                const bPri = priorityOrder[b.priority || b.highestPriority] || 999;
                if (aPri !== bPri) return aPri - bPri;
                
                // Finally by name
                return a.name.localeCompare(b.name);
            }).map(node =&gt; ({
                ...node,
                children: sortNodes(node.children || [])
            }));
        };
        
        console.log(&#x27;🌳 buildTreeData returning:&#x27;, {
            resultLength: result.length,
            firstFewNodes: result.slice(0, 3).map(n =&gt; ({name: n.name, type: n.type, childrenCount: n.children?.length}))
        });
        
        return sortNodes(result);
    }, []);

    // Load data from props
    useEffect(() =&gt; {
        try {
            console.log(&#x27;🔍 Loading tree data from props...&#x27;);
            console.log(&#x27;📊 Props data:&#x27;, data);
            
            if (data &amp;&amp; typeof data === &#x27;object&#x27;) {
                console.log(&#x27;📊 Refactoring candidates:&#x27;, data.refactoringCandidatesByFile?.length || 0);
                console.log(&#x27;🏗️ Directory health tree:&#x27;, data.directoryHealthTree ? &#x27;present&#x27; : &#x27;missing&#x27;);
                
                const treeStructure = buildTreeData(
                    data.refactoringCandidatesByFile || [],
                    data.directoryHealthTree
                );
                console.log(&#x27;🌳 Built tree structure, nodes:&#x27;, treeStructure.length);
                setTreeData(treeStructure);
            } else {
                console.warn(&#x27;⚠️ No valid data provided in props&#x27;);
                setTreeData([]);
            }
        } catch (error) {
            console.error(&#x27;❌ Failed to load tree data:&#x27;, error);
            setTreeData([]);
        }
    }, [data, buildTreeData]);
    
    if (treeData.length === 0) {
        console.log(&#x27;⚠️ Showing &quot;no analysis data&quot; message - treeData.length is 0&#x27;);
        return React.createElement(&#x27;div&#x27;, {
            style: {
                textAlign: &#x27;center&#x27;,
                padding: &#x27;2rem&#x27;,
                color: &#x27;var(--muted)&#x27;
            }
        }, 
            React.createElement(&#x27;h3&#x27;, { key: &#x27;title&#x27; }, &#x27;No Refactoring Candidates Found&#x27;),
            React.createElement(&#x27;p&#x27;, { key: &#x27;desc&#x27; }, &#x27;Your code is in excellent shape!&#x27;)
        );
    }
    
    return React.createElement(Tree, {
        data: treeData,
        openByDefault: false,
        width: &#x27;100%&#x27;,
        height: 600,
        indent: 24,
        rowHeight: 40,
        children: TreeNode
    });
};

// Export for global use
window.CodeAnalysisTree = CodeAnalysisTree;

from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import List

FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT = 5  # The fixed nr of vacation days that can be paid out.


@dataclass
class Employee:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Basic representation of an employee at the company.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    name: str
    role: str
    vacation_days: int = 25

    def take_a_holiday(self, payout: bool) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Let the employee take a single holiday, or pay out 5 holidays.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        if payout:
            # check that there are enough vacation days left for a payout
            if self.vacation_days &lt; FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT:
                raise ValueError(
                    f&quot;You don&#x27;t have enough holidays left over for a payout.\
                        Remaining holidays: {self.vacation_days}.&quot;
                )
            try:
                self.vacation_days -= FIXED_VACATION_DAYS_PAYOUT
                print(f&quot;Paying out a holiday. Holidays left: {self.vacation_days}&quot;)
            except Exception:
                # this should never happen
                pass
        else:
            if self.vacation_days &lt; 1:
                raise ValueError(
                    &quot;You don&#x27;t have any holidays left. Now back to work, you!&quot;
                )
            self.vacation_days -= 1
            print(&quot;Have fun on your holiday. Don&#x27;t forget to check your emails!&quot;)


@dataclass
class HourlyEmployee(Employee):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Employee that&#x27;s paid based on number of worked hours.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    hourly_rate: float = 50
    amount: int = 10


@dataclass
class SalariedEmployee(Employee):
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Employee that&#x27;s paid based on a fixed monthly salary.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    monthly_salary: float = 5000


class Company:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Represents a company with employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    def __init__(self) -&gt; None:
        self.employees: List[Employee] = []

    def add_employee(self, employee: Employee) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Add an employee to the list of employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        self.employees.append(employee)

    def find_managers(self) -&gt; List[Employee]:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Find all manager employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        managers = []
        for employee in self.employees:
            if employee.role == &quot;manager&quot;:
                managers.append(employee)
        return managers

    def find_vice_presidents(self) -&gt; List[Employee]:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Find all vice-president employees.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        vice_presidents = []
        for employee in self.employees:
            if employee.role == &quot;vice_president&quot;:
                vice_presidents.append(employee)
        return vice_presidents

    def find_interns(self) -&gt; List[Employee]:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Find all interns.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        interns = []
        for employee in self.employees:
            if employee.role == &quot;intern&quot;:
                interns.append(employee)
        return interns

    def pay_employee(self, employee: Employee) -&gt; None:
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Pay an employee.&quot;&quot;&quot;
        if isinstance(employee, SalariedEmployee):
            print(
                f&quot;Paying employee {employee.name} a monthly salary of ${employee.monthly_salary}.&quot;
            )
        elif isinstance(employee, HourlyEmployee):
            print(
                f&quot;Paying employee {employee.name} a hourly rate of \
                ${employee.hourly_rate} for {employee.amount} hours.&quot;
            )


def main() -&gt; None:
    &quot;&quot;&quot;Main function.&quot;&quot;&quot;

    company = Company()

    company.add_employee(SalariedEmployee(name=&quot;Louis&quot;, role=&quot;manager&quot;))
    company.add_employee(HourlyEmployee(name=&quot;Brenda&quot;, role=&quot;president&quot;))
    company.add_employee(HourlyEmployee(name=&quot;Tim&quot;, role=&quot;intern&quot;))

    print(company.find_vice_presidents())
    print(company.find_managers())
    print(company.find_interns())
    company.pay_employee(company.employees[0])
    company.employees[0].take_a_holiday(False)


if __name__ == &quot;__main__&quot;:
    main()
📄 vscode-extension/src/extension.ts
import * as vscode from &#x27;vscode&#x27;;
import { ReportPanel } from &#x27;./reportPanel&#x27;;
import { ReportProvider } from &#x27;./reportProvider&#x27;;
import { ValknutAnalyzer } from &#x27;./analyzer&#x27;;

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    console.log(&#x27;Valknut extension is now active!&#x27;);

    // Initialize report provider
    const reportProvider = new ReportProvider(context);
    
    // Register tree data provider
    vscode.window.registerTreeDataProvider(&#x27;valknutReports&#x27;, reportProvider);

    // Initialize analyzer
    const analyzer = new ValknutAnalyzer();

    // Command to open report
    const openReportCommand = vscode.commands.registerCommand(&#x27;valknut.openReport&#x27;, async (uri?: vscode.Uri) =&gt; {
        try {
            let reportPath: string;
            
            if (uri) {
                reportPath = uri.fsPath;
            } else {
                // Show file picker
                const result = await vscode.window.showOpenDialog({
                    canSelectFiles: true,
                    canSelectFolders: false,
                    canSelectMany: false,
                    filters: {
                        &#x27;JSON files&#x27;: [&#x27;json&#x27;],
                        &#x27;All files&#x27;: [&#x27;*&#x27;]
                    },
                    title: &#x27;Select Valknut Report&#x27;
                });

                if (!result || result.length === 0) {
                    return;
                }
                
                reportPath = result[0].fsPath;
            }

            await ReportPanel.createOrShow(context.extensionUri, reportPath);
        } catch (error) {
            vscode.window.showErrorMessage(`Failed to open report: ${error}`);
        }
    });

    // Command to analyze current workspace
    const analyzeWorkspaceCommand = vscode.commands.registerCommand(&#x27;valknut.analyzeWorkspace&#x27;, async () =&gt; {
        try {
            if (!vscode.workspace.workspaceFolders || vscode.workspace.workspaceFolders.length === 0) {
                vscode.window.showWarningMessage(&#x27;No workspace folder open&#x27;);
                return;
            }

            const workspaceRoot = vscode.workspace.workspaceFolders[0].uri.fsPath;
            
            await vscode.window.withProgress({
                location: vscode.ProgressLocation.Notification,
                title: &quot;Analyzing workspace with Valknut&quot;,
                cancellable: true
            }, async (progress, token) =&gt; {
                try {
                    progress.report({ message: &quot;Running analysis...&quot; });
                    
                    const reportPath = await analyzer.analyzeWorkspace(workspaceRoot, {
                        onProgress: (message: string) =&gt; {
                            progress.report({ message });
                        },
                        cancellationToken: token
                    });

                    if (reportPath) {
                        progress.report({ message: &quot;Opening report...&quot; });
                        await ReportPanel.createOrShow(context.extensionUri, reportPath);
                        reportProvider.refresh();
                    }
                } catch (error) {
                    if (error instanceof Error &amp;&amp; error.message.includes(&#x27;cancelled&#x27;)) {
                        vscode.window.showInformationMessage(&#x27;Analysis cancelled&#x27;);
                    } else {
                        throw error;
                    }
                }
            });
        } catch (error) {
            vscode.window.showErrorMessage(`Analysis failed: ${error}`);
        }
    });

    // Command to refresh report
    const refreshReportCommand = vscode.commands.registerCommand(&#x27;valknut.refreshReport&#x27;, () =&gt; {
        reportProvider.refresh();
        ReportPanel.refresh();
    });

    // Command to export report
    const exportReportCommand = vscode.commands.registerCommand(&#x27;valknut.exportReport&#x27;, async () =&gt; {
        if (!ReportPanel.currentPanel) {
            vscode.window.showWarningMessage(&#x27;No report currently open&#x27;);
            return;
        }

        try {
            const result = await vscode.window.showSaveDialog({
                filters: {
                    &#x27;HTML files&#x27;: [&#x27;html&#x27;],
                    &#x27;JSON files&#x27;: [&#x27;json&#x27;],
                    &#x27;All files&#x27;: [&#x27;*&#x27;]
                },
                defaultUri: vscode.Uri.file(&#x27;valknut-report.html&#x27;)
            });

            if (result) {
                await ReportPanel.currentPanel.exportReport(result.fsPath);
                vscode.window.showInformationMessage(&#x27;Report exported successfully&#x27;);
            }
        } catch (error) {
            vscode.window.showErrorMessage(`Export failed: ${error}`);
        }
    });

    // Register all commands
    context.subscriptions.push(
        openReportCommand,
        analyzeWorkspaceCommand,
        refreshReportCommand,
        exportReportCommand
    );

    // Watch for configuration changes
    const configWatcher = vscode.workspace.onDidChangeConfiguration(e =&gt; {
        if (e.affectsConfiguration(&#x27;valknut&#x27;)) {
            ReportPanel.updateConfiguration();
        }
    });

    context.subscriptions.push(configWatcher);

    // Auto-refresh on file changes if enabled
    const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration(&#x27;valknut&#x27;);
    if (config.get(&#x27;autoRefresh&#x27;, true)) {
        const fileWatcher = vscode.workspace.createFileSystemWatcher(&#x27;**/*.json&#x27;);
        
        fileWatcher.onDidChange((uri) =&gt; {
            if (uri.fsPath.includes(&#x27;valknut&#x27;) || uri.fsPath.includes(&#x27;report&#x27;)) {
                reportProvider.refresh();
            }
        });

        context.subscriptions.push(fileWatcher);
    }

    // Set context for when reports are available
    reportProvider.onDidChangeTreeData(() =&gt; {
        vscode.commands.executeCommand(&#x27;setContext&#x27;, &#x27;valknut.hasReports&#x27;, reportProvider.hasReports());
    });
}

export function deactivate() {
    ReportPanel.dispose();
}
